comment_data.body:
**scoder** commented

Looks like a conflict between cdef keyword arguments and optional cdef arguments. Maybe even limited to the case of methods.

**scoder** commented

I failed to reproduce it so far:

https://github.com/cython/cython/commit/b53ef998dc7ee0e377d48e13555d55713f3be235

**scoder** commented

I think this is unrelated to cdef kwargs. Is seems more likely that the crash was triggered by switching from a Python call (which implicitly keeps all arguments alive during the call) to a C call (which doesn't care about references to its arguments).

@jdemeyer changed **summary** from

segfault when using cdef keyword arguments

to

Segfault when changing from def to cdef call
commented

@jdemeyer commented

Replying to [scoder](comment:3):

> I think this is unrelated to cdef kwargs. Is seems more likely that the crash was triggered by switching from a Python call (which implicitly keeps all arguments alive during the call) to a C call (which doesn't care about references to its arguments).

You're right. Adding an additional reference to `self` (I just did `extraself = self`) fixes to problem.

I'm still wondering how it can happen that `self` doesn't have enough references to stay alive.

@jdemeyer commented

It might also be an upstream Python bug, I'm looking into it.

@jdemeyer commented

It is an upstream bug: in `type_getattro()`, the slot `tp_descr_get()` is called without holding a reference to `self`.

@jdemeyer commented

Please close, it's an upstream bug: ​http://bugs.python.org/issue25750
This is an upstream bug: http://bugs.python.org/issue25750

title: Segfault when changing from def to cdef call
